result.execSummary:
The defendant Michael A Gawlitta was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Child Pornography, a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.12(1m).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Sentencing proceeded.   Statements by state, defense and defendant.  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 14 YEARS  concurrent to 2014CF001255, with credit for 10 DAYS time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 
4 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is  10 YEARS.  Conditions of extended supervision:

*Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with recommended treatment.

*Take prescribed mediations.

*Random urine screens.
*No drugs.

*Seek and maintain fulltime employment
*Obtain high school diploma or GED
*Cognitive Behavior Therapy

*No unsupervised contact with anyone under the age of 16 without agent's consent, with the exception of his children. 
*Pay supervision fees
*No contact with FS, LP or their families
*No electronic commjunications with children under the age of 16 without agent's approval. 

Court ordered defendant to provide DNA sample and imposed mandatory surchages.

Court determined that defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incareceration Program nor the Substance Abuse Program. 
Court ordered defendant to pay a fine in the sum of $500.00 PLUS DNA surcharge and all other applicable costs and any other surcharges and assessments to be collected by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and to convert to civil judgment upon release from extended supervision.  Bail to be applied.
